revision.text:
'''Bio-geoengineering''' is a form of [[climate engineering]] which seeks to use or modify plants or other living things to modify the Earth's climate.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/science/earth/20obcrops.html?_r=1&ref=science&pagewanted=print | title=More-Reflective Crops May Have Cooling Effect| newspaper=The New York Times| date=2009-01-19| last1=Fountain| first1=Henry}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url=http://www.cell.com/current-biology/abstract/S0960-9822(08)01680-1 | doi=10.1016/j.cub.2008.12.025| pmid=19147356| title=Tackling Regional Climate Change by Leaf Albedo Bio-geoengineering| journal=Current Biology| volume=19| issue=2| pages=146–150| year=2009| last1=Ridgwell| first1=Andy| last2=Singarayer| first2=Joy S.| last3=Hetherington| first3=Alistair M.| last4=Valdes| first4=Paul J.}}</ref>

[[Bio-energy with carbon capture and storage|Bio-energy with carbon storage]], [[afforestation]] projects, and [[ocean nourishment]] (including [[iron fertilization]]) could be considered examples of bio-geoengineering.{{Fact|date=January 2009}}

Biogenic aerosols can be grown to replace those beneficial aerosols lost as the result of the death of 50% of Earth's boreal forests. Agricultural production of atmospheric aerosols called "monoterpenes" is possible if crops that are rich in monoterpenes are grown.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2006/apr/14/environment.climatechange
 | title=Fragrance of pine forests helps to slow climate change| newspaper=The Guardian| date=2006-04-13| last1=Randerson| first1=James}}</ref>

