{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}}
'''Frederick Campbell Rose''' [[Order of the Star of India|CSI]] (1865 &ndash; 18 July 1946) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[civil engineer]] who spent most of his career in [[India]].
Rose was born in [[Elgin, Moray|Elgin]] and educated at [[Trinity College, Glenalmond]] and the [[Royal Indian Engineering College]]. He joined the Indian Public Works Department in 1886 and was posted to the Irrigation Branch in the [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]], where he spent most of his career, becoming a leading authority on [[irrigation]]. In 1916 he was appointed Secretary of the Public Works Department, which carried with it membership of the [[Viceroy of India|Viceroy's]] Legislative Council.
He retired from Indian service in 1919 to take up the post of chief engineer of river improvements in the [[Hebei|Chili]] Province of Northern [[China]], finally retiring in 1927.
Rose was appointed [[Companion of the Order of the Star of India]] (CSI) in the 1920 New Year Honours.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31712 |date=30 December 1919 |page=4 |supp=y}}</ref>
