'''Infiltrative ophthalmopathy''' is found in 5-10% of patients with [[Graves disease]] and resembles [[exophthalmos]], except that the blurry or [[double vision]] is acquired because of weakness in the [[ocular muscles]] of the eye.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Munjal|first1=Y. P.|title=API Textbook of Medicine (Volume I & II)|date=2015|publisher=JP Medical Ltd|isbn=9789351524151|page=596|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z39GCgAAQBAJ&dq=Infiltrative+ophthalmopathy&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=5 December 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name="mcdougall">{{cite book|last1=McDougall|first1=I. Ross|title=Thyroid Disease in Clinical Practice|date=2013|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781489928818|page=90|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_nP1BwAAQBAJ&dq=Infiltrative+ophthalmopathy&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=5 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> In addition, there is no known correlation with the patient's [[thyroid]] levels.  Exophthalmos associated with Grave's disease disappears when the [[thyrotoxicosis]] is corrected.  Infiltrative ophthalmopathy at times may not be cured. Treatments consist of high dose glucocorticoids and low dose radiotherapy.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Panglossi|first1=Harold V.|title=Antioxidants: New Research|date=2006|publisher=Nova Publishers|isbn=9781594549991|pages=93-95|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjtabIeXBlIC&dq=Infiltrative+ophthalmopathy&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=5 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>  The current hypothesis is that infiltrative ophthalmopathy may be [[autoimmune]] in nature targeting retrobulbar tissue. Smoking may also have a causative effect.<ref name="mcdougall" />

