'''Ishaq Ibn Imran''' (died c. 903-9) was an Iraqi-Arab<ref>{{cite book|last1=Horden|first1=Peregrine|title=Music as Medicine: The History of Music Therapy Since Antiquity|date=2017|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351557474|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=CS8rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=%22Ishaq+Ibn+Imran%22+arab&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk1Puul-TZAhVIwBQKHQ16AJgQ6AEISjAG#v=onepage&q=%22Ishaq%20Ibn%20Imran%22%20arab&f=false|language=en}}</ref> physician working in [[Kairouan]], which at the time was the capital of [[Tunisia]]. His treatise on [[Melancholia|melancholy]], written c.900,<ref>Adel Omrani et al, [https://www.academia.edu/3885846/Ibn_Imrans_10th_century_Treatise_on_Melancholy Ibn Imran's 10th century Treatise on Melancholy], ''Journal of Affective Disorders'' 141 (2012), pp.116-9.</ref> was translated into Latin by [[Constantine the African]] in the eleventh century.<ref>Angus Gowland, [https://babel.revues.org/2078 Burton's Anatomy and the Intellectual Traditions of Melancholy], ''Revue Babel'' 25 (2012), pp.221-57.</ref>
