'''Johrei''' {{nihongo|"purification of the spirit"|浄霊|Jōrei}}, sometimes spelled ''jyorei'', is a form of [[alternative medicine]] similar to [[Reiki]].<ref name="SBM">{{cite web|last=Luke|first=Jesse|title=Johrei: The next energy healing craze?|url=https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/johrei-the-next-energy-healing-craze/|website=Science Based Medicine|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> It was introduced in [[Japan]] in the 1930s by [[Mokichi Okada]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Jyorei — 'purification of the spirit' |url= http://www.jyorei.org |website= www.jyorei.org |publisher= |date= |accessdate= }}</ref><ref name="SBM"/><ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Religious Phenomena|last=Melton|first=J. Gordon|publisher=Visible Ink Press LLC|year=2008|isbn=1578592097|location=Canton, MI|pages=174}}</ref> 

Despite presenting itself as a form of alternative medicine, the Johrei Fellowship maintains that it does not prescribe, diagnose, or treat physical illnesses<ref name="SBM"/> and that their focus is on spiritual health and world peace instead of physical health.<ref>{{cite book |editor-last= Okada |editor-first= Mokichi |year= 1998b |publisher= Johrei Fellowship |title= Fragments from the Teachings of Meishu-sama |isbn=  9780962918346 |page= 56 |ref= {{SfnRef|Okada|1998b}} |origyear= 1965}}</ref>{{cfn|date=June 2015}}

== Origin and history ==
Okada, who was also a previous member of Omoto, one of Japan's new religions, claimed to have a vision in 1925 of the Buddhist [[Bodhisattva]] Kannon (Kuan Yin) and she gave him the divine light, along with a command that Okada proclaim himself a prophet.<ref name=":0" /> He later established the Great Japan Association for the Veneration of the Bodhisattva Kanon, with divine healing as its main purpose.<ref name=":0" /> Practitioners claim to channel [[Vitalism|vitalist]] [[Energy (esotericism)|"energy"]] into patients by waving their hands over the patient's body.<ref name="SBM" /> 

There is a claim that, in lectures and classes, there are numerous reports of dramatic healings.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Vibrational Energy Medicine|last=Guimares|first=Fernando|publisher=Pedia Press|year=2006|isbn=9780826138057|location=New York|pages=170}}</ref> Aside from its association with these miracles, Johrei is known for its two significant features. The first involves simplicity of the healing practice because the placement of the hand over another person can be performed anywhere.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Japanese Prayer Below the Equator: How Brazilians Believe in the Church of World Messianity|last=Matsuoka|first=Hideaki|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2007|isbn=0739113798|location=Lanham|pages=159}}</ref> [[Egalitarianism]] constitutes the second feature of Johrei. This is based on the fundamental idea that one person administers healing and another receives it and that "there is no difference between clergy and followers in their ability to transmit the light of God." <ref name=":1" /> 

Johrei was introduced to America in 1953, and there are numerous Johrei centers throughout the United States and other countries.<ref>{{cite web |title= About us |url= http://johreifellowship.org/about-us |website= johreifellowship.org |publisher= |date= |accessdate= November 8, 2014}}</ref>

